====Reconstruction notes====
* Conventionally reconstructed as *-kuy because ''[[w:Idu script|Idu]]'' manuals in Han'gul read this character as {{m|okm|-희|tr=-huy}}, which is believed to reflect an ancient reading tradition. Middle Korean intervocalic /h/ is usually [[lenited]] from Old Korean */k/ based on internal and dialectal reconstruction. The non-lenited form also survives directly in pronouns: {{m|okm|이ᅌᅥ긔〮|tr=ìngèkúy|t=here}}, {{m|okm|뎌ᇰ어긔〮|tr=tyèngèkúy|t=there}}, etc.
* Assumed to be a [[logogram]] borrowed from Chinese, as no Chinese reading or native Korean equivalent of {{m|oko|中}} whose phonology is even remotely similar to *kuy is known. The Chinese word often bears a locative meaning as well, and there is a certain parallel in the Vietnamese Nôm use of the same character to write the native preposition {{m|vi|trong|t=in; inside}}.
* First-millennium Old Korean also featured the locative particle {{m|oko|良|tr=*-a}}. The two particles were compounded as {{m|oko|良中|tr=*-a-kuy}} as early as the seventh century. The compounded form becomes predominant in the corpus after the eleventh century, after which 中 *-kuy in isolation is rarely encountered (although a likely Middle Korean reflex is attested in Hangul form as late as the fifteenth century). The compounded form eventually fused into a single morpheme, becoming the Middle Korean locative particle {{m|okm|-에|-에〮/애〮|tr=-éy/áy}}.
* At some point, perhaps even before widespread compounding, */k/ was [[lenited]] to */h/. Lenition may have begun as early as the eighth century, given the attestation of the {{m|oko|希}} form in the poem {{lang|ko|讚耆婆郞歌}} ''Changiparang-ga'', whose claimed date of composition is 740.
* Nam Pung-hyun suggests that {{m|oko|矣|tr=*-uy}}, another apparent locative particle attested in the Old Korean corpus, should be connected to {{m-self|oko|中|tr=*-kuy.}} He classifies both as "''uy''-type locatives", in contrast to {{m|oko|良|tr=*-a }} as an "''a''-type locative", and speculates that the ''uy''-type locatives were reserved for animate beings while {{m|oko|良}} could be used indiscriminately.

